on lim(|cos(x)|^x) at infinity it's easy enough to find a sequence such that all the values are 1, or all the values are 0 hence proving the limit doesn't exist more interestingly, if you consider only integer x you would maybe expect the limit to be 0 but using series approximations you can relate this sequence to the irrationality measure of pi from the irrationality of pi, we know the irrationality measure of pi is >= 2(edited) and hence limsup(|cos(x)|^(x^n)) = 1 for all n <=2 the sup of the values of n such that this true is 2mu(pi)-2 iirc the best proven upper bound on mu(pi) is roughly 7.6063 giving that lim(|cos(x)|^(x^n)) = 0 for all n > 13.2126

Nathan R 14-Nov-18 09:56 AM
We did nothing today just talked about what types of heat are no math or anything
November 14 2018 Heat and Temperature Temperature - A measurement of the kinetic energy in a substance due to the vibration of the atoms within it. Thermal Energy(Heat) - Combination of kinetic and potential energy in the vibrations of the atom in a substance. The amount of thermal energy is a substance is proportional to its mass.     ie. If you double the amount of molecules, you double the thermal energy. Celsius - created so that 0°C matches with the freezing point of water and 100°C matches with the boiling point of water. F = 9/5 + 32 F  - 32 = 9/5C C = 5/9 (F - 32) Kelvin - 0°K is when there is no thermal energy (0°K = + 273°C, C = K - 273) Ex. 1°C K = C + 273 = 274°K How fast a substance can transfer its heat is called heat capacity. Matter can transfer heat in 3 ways: Conduction (Through touch) Convection (The molecules in a liquid move and carry the thermal energy with it) Radiation (Light or similar forms of energy, Atoms release light energy transferred from kinetic energy) Conductor -  A material that has a loose hold on some of its electrons. (Far left on the P-Table) These substances can transfer their heat very easily. Insulator - A material that has a tight hold on electrons. These transfer heat at a slower rate.

Catherine L 24-Jan-19 01:29 AM
I don’t know how the slip ring works but this is how the AC generator works: The coil is in between two permanent magnets and is being moved with an external force (e.g. lever). Since the coil is moving, in the coil’s perspective, it seems like the magnetic field around it is changing. According to Lenz’s law, since the magnetic field of a nearby magnet is changing, the coil will set up its own magnetic field to oppose the motion (e.g. you will start to feel resistance as you are turning the lever). Therefore, there is also current going through the coil now.
